In .NET MAUI, use `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` and the `RequestedThemeChanged` event. To force a theme, set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme`.

```csharp
// Detect current system theme
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current!.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified

// Subscribe to real-time theme changes
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI or refresh resources here
};

// Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**In XAML**, use `AppThemeBinding` for automatic resource switching:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />

<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#FFFFFF, Dark=#1E1E1E}">
```

**Key points:**

- `RequestedTheme` — read-only, reflects the OS setting.
- `UserAppTheme` — read/write, lets you override it. Set to `Unspecified` to follow the system again.
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires when the **system** theme changes (not when you set `UserAppTheme`).
- `AppThemeBinding` in XAML reacts to both system and user-forced theme changes automatically.
